OK let me help you out with some game knowledge you seem to be lacking.  Some spells are specifically designed to be more difficult to cast.  Some are designed to be easier to cast.  For example, the Atol's Spirit Shackles has a higher fizzle rate, by design.  On the other hand, the Beastlord cold blasts are designed with a lower fizzle rate.  However, the average spell, unadjusted, according to the game designers, has a 5% chance of fizzling.  That's no joke, I'm sorry if you don't particularly like it.<br>
<br>
Here's GZ on Fizzle rates:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>You will learn skills much quicker with a high intelligence level compared to someone with low intelligence. Intelligence also reduces the chance of spell fizzles. Intelligence over 75 reduces fizzle rate by 1% for each point over 75. Minimum is 5%. [from GZ]<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
That's from this board, in the Skills section regarding INtelligence.  Here's a longer version of what he means by this:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>There is always a 5% chance of succeeding (regardless of how low your appropriate skill is) and a 5% chance of failure (regardless of how high your appropriate skill is). What modifies the chance to fizzle check is the appropriate skill (Abjuration, Evocation, etc.), your character's Intelligence, the difficulty of the spell, and the level of the spell. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Spells have a toughness rating, so that some are less difficult to cast than others.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  &lt;when he wrote this, it was before Kunark, and none were more difficult to cast at the time, since then spells have been added&gt;.<br>
<br>
When you gain a new rank of spells, any spell that you cast of that rank has a 20% chance of fizzling. This is adjusted by your skill and INT, and the toughness rating of the spell. If your INT is greater then 75 the chance of fizzle is reduced by 1% for every point of your statistic above 75. Each spell assumes that you have a skill equal to (5 * level you go the spell). A Wizard getting Bind Affinity (a Wizard gets 4th rank spells at level 12, so 5 * 12 =60) would have that spell assuming that he had a 60 Alteration skill for purposes of casting. With a 60 skill in Alteration (the appropriate skill) and a 75 intelligence, our wizard would have an 80% chance of successfully casting Bind Affinity. For every skill point that our Wizard has above 60, the percent chance of fizzling goes down by 1%, to a minimum of a 5% chance of fizzling.<br>
<br>
Thus, three levels (15 skill points) after a caster gets Bind Affinity, he will be able to max out Alteration for that spell, and have a mere 5% chance of fizzling the spell. Higher Intelligence will also help with this.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
