I agree, consistency makes sense. Which is why there's no logic to your bizarre attempts to defend the position of Concussion's quest being deliberately made higher level because its so important they wanted you to fizzle less. Illusion:Iksar hardly fits that, does it? But that's what you'd have us believe, that they're both done that way. There's a basic flaw with that position, I'm sure you can see.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Heh, I was using Illusion:Iksar as proof that spell quests are intentionally challenging for the level they were intended, and to prove not all Kunark spell quests were for level 39 spells. The rest of it was words you put in my mouth.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>What have you said wrong? You mean other than &quot;Concussion and Jolt came out at the same time&quot; or &quot;...you're a big fat liar Grim.&quot; When you were pretending that spells didn't have a base 5% fizzle rate. Take your pick.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Concussion and Jolt did come out at the same time, give or take a week. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  And tell you what, as soon as I can procure a low-50s wizard, I will run some parses, and then we'll see what there is to see. I don't honestly see how you can say this with a straight face. Either that or you just never played a low-50s level wizard.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Quote:Concussion has a fizzle adjust of 25, the highest fizzle rating spells are ever given.<br>
<br>
And your point here is what? That they deliberately made it fizzle a lot then made it intentionally only available realistically at level 50+ so it won't fizzle as much then???? I mean, try to be a little logical here.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
They didn't make it fizzle a lot. That's the standard fizzle rating for any non-evocation wizard spell before level 50, which is easily dealt with by being above that level, which has the added function of making the spell easier to channel.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>However, you might want to look at those fizzle numbers a bit more closely: Atol's Spirit Shackles (intentionally designed to fizzle more and fizzles a LOT more) is a 5, Concussion is a 25, and the first level Frost Bolt spell is a 25. So your interpretation is backwards, spells with a higher number cast easier. I know that's kind of wierd, but in my experience it plays out. I almost never fizzle concussion, and I fizzle atol's quite a bit. Even over 5 levels past the time I got it.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Um, no, exactly wrong. Higher means more fizzles. Remember the patches that lowered the fizzle difficulty of many level 51-60 spells? Because clerics and wizards were complaining about high fizzle rates despite maxed skills? The only field that changed was what Lucy calls the fizzle adjust, and they were <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>lowered</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->. I could post an spdat.eff from back then if you like.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>But let's assume your statement is true as it stands &quot;there just doesn't seem to be a problem for appropriately-leveled people doing the quest.&quot; Doesn't that sort of ruin your entire argument, that it was made intentionally harder?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Not really. Face it, what was considered difficult 3 years ago is not difficult now. The &quot;problem&quot;, as you call it, solved itself.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Quote:I could bring up the magician epic here, designed for level 51-60 while being a level 46 spell....<br>
<br>
And it would be meaningless, since your level 59 AA abilities are level 1 spells. Levels for effects like that are arbitrary, they aren't related to the actual spell.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
The magician epic quest results in a no-drop spell scroll, which has to be scribed to be used. It is a level 46 spell, but it summons an item which <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://forum.magecompendium.com/tower/viewtopic.php?t=4356&amp;sid=1c31d36acba5e4bd2f4e9d75253ccf1c">cannot be used</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> to summon the epic pet until level 50. I would think that would be clear evidence that the spell was intended for higher levels than can actually scribe it. This is not an AA skill, this is a quest spell with a scroll you must scribe. How is this different from Concussion? Now you're just making up reasons not to see what's plain as day.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Quote:Jolt has a fizzle rating of 0. Jolt casts faster than Concussion, plus rangers get innate spell haste on detrimental spells. Heh, and look at the cast time on Boggle. Crucial differences that would help with fizzles and channeling, I'm sure you would agree. Or maybe not, I can't tell with you anymore.<br>
<br>
You mean a higher fizzle rate? Yeah, that's a critical difference, but not one that helps you. Remember our lesson from Atols above? Lower = more fizzles.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Um, no. Here, the <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://eq.crgaming.com/viewarticle.asp?Article=4053">patch message</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> from January 23, 2002 in which Atol's casting difficulty was reduced (the second time this happened btw, oh ye of short memory), the January 8 2002 <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://home.earthlink.net/~trilliwig/data/spdat-01-08-02.eff">spdat</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->, and the January 23 2002 <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://home.earthlink.net/~trilliwig/data/spdat-01-23-02.eff">spdat</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->.<br>
Open them both up with <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://home.earthlink.net/~trilliwig/data/Eqcaster-5-2-4.exe">EqCaster v5.2.4</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> (later versions don't understand the old spdat format), see that the &quot;Fizzle Percent&quot; was changed from 15 to 5, and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>eat your words</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Quote:I don't have to like it, if it's not true. Seriously, run your own experiments, if you have a level 51-52 wizard with maxed skills and int and Atol's or Abscond. See if this jibes with the above quote. If you get a 5% fizzle rate with them, I'll eat my hat.<br>
<br>
those spells are intentionally designed to be harder to fizzle.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Abscond has an identical fizzle adjustment to Concussion. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :rolleyes --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/eyes.gif ALT=":rolleyes"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>As noted below in GZ's explaination of how fizzle rates work. And I have said repeatedly. Those spells, by definition and intent fizzle more, by design. Is this beginning to make sense yet?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
It just doesn't work that way. According to what was written, a wizard with 90 int and maxed skills would never fizzle above the 5% minimum, and this behavior is not borne out in practice. Face it, it's outdated info.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Ah, so when you GET a quote from GZ you ignore it because you don't like it?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Not because I don't like it. Because I know from experience it's not true.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Everything he said holds true still, even though when he posted it there weren't any adjusted fizzle rate spells... yet. He put that in because he was at that time working on spells like Atol's.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Um, wrong again. All the level 39-49 nuke spells have lower fizzle ratings, and always have, because at the time you didn't go above 50 to get the level-based fizzle deduction. The level 34 nuke has a fizzle adjust of 25, the level 39 nuke 15, the level 44 nukes 5, and the level 49 nukes 0.  A fizzle adjustment of 25 seems to take 15 levels to disappear. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Quote:Sheesh, you're talking to me like I don't understand the spell system.<br>
<br>
Sorry I can only go based on experience.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
ROFL. I'm not the one claiming the fizzle adjustment field means the opposite of what it does.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Nope thats just icing on the cake. The evidence in the game, experience with the company, the spell system, and logic all force the issue; that and your lack of 'documentation' and lack of logic as well as game mechanics. You're going exclusively on your theory. That's fine, but I'd rather you didn't spread misonceptions about the spell or the quest for other wizards to read. I've step by step pulled apart all your attempts at defending this theory, why on earth would anyone cling to it I cannot imagine.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I am asking the same thing of you, but I have this weird position of being backed by historical fact, while you can do nothing but bring up manufactured claims which I have repeatedly shot down.<br>
